  <!-- ═══ RISKS & FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Risks to Consider</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Commodity Price Dependence:</strong> Newmont's cash flows are highly levered to the price of gold. A sustained drop in gold prices directly impairs free cash flow generation.</li>
    <li><strong>Capital Intensity:</strong> Mining requires continuous, massive capital expenditures. Cost overruns in new projects or sustaining existing mines can erase free cash flow.</li>
    <li><strong>Geopolitical Risk:</strong> Operations in diverse global jurisdictions expose the company to political instability, taxation changes, and regulatory hurdles.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why use a DCF for a mining company?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">While challenging due to capex lumpiness and commodity cycles, DCF forces a rigorous evaluation of the cash the assets actually produce, rather than relying on arbitrary P/E or EV/EBITDA multiples which fluctuate wildly with gold sentiment.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why is the discount rate {(discountRate * 100).toFixed(1)}%?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">It is calculated using the Capital Asset Pricing Model (CAPM). It starts with the 10-year Treasury yield of {(treasury10Y * 100).toFixed(2)}% as a risk-free base, adding a risk premium specific to Newmont's beta (market volatility correlation).</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>What if Free Cash Flow is negative?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Negative FCF is common in mining during major expansion phases. If recent FCF is deeply negative solely due to growth capex, we may proxy a normalized base cash flow from Operating Cash Flow to represent the underlying business's capacity to generate cash.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

